			<h1>Chicago Police Superintendent to keynote UICâ€™s annual Bridging the Gap symposium</h1>

			<p class="author-date">
				October 11, 2018			</p>

			<div class="pf-content"><p>Chicago Police Superintendent Eddie Johnson will be the keynote speaker at the University of Illinois at Chicago&#8217;s annual Bridging the Gap symposium, which focuses on health issues in underrepresented minority communities. This year the conference will address gun violence.</p>
<p>Speakers will also discuss theÂ Center for Health Equity Research,Â a National Institutes of Health-funded research center at UIC that investigates how structural violence and other social determinants, like living in neighborhoods with high rates of gun violence, for example, contribute to the health of marginalized groups.</p>
<p>Updates on the NIH&#8217;s All of Us Research Program, a nationwide initiative to gather data from 1 million people living in the U.S. to develop new precision treatments that take into account individual differences in lifestyle, environment and biology, will also be presented. UIC is one of the institutions leading efforts to recruit participants in the Chicagoland area.</p>
<div id="attachment_70152" style="width: 397px" class="wp-caption alignright"><a href="https://today.uic.edu/chicago-police-superintendent-to-keynote-uics-annual-bridging-the-gap-symposium/chicago-police-department"><img class="wp-image-70152 size-medium" src="https://today.uic.edu/files/2018/10/Superintendent-Johnson_F-387x258.jpg" alt="Eddie Johnson" width="387" height="258" srcset="https://today.uic.edu/files/2018/10/Superintendent-Johnson_F-387x258.jpg 387w, https://today.uic.edu/files/2018/10/Superintendent-Johnson_F-768x512.jpg 768w, https://today.uic.edu/files/2018/10/Superintendent-Johnson_F-590x393.jpg 590w, https://today.uic.edu/files/2018/10/Superintendent-Johnson_F-1000x667.jpg 1000w, https://today.uic.edu/files/2018/10/Superintendent-Johnson_F-500x333.jpg 500w, https://today.uic.edu/files/2018/10/Superintendent-Johnson_F-300x200.jpg 300w, https://today.uic.edu/files/2018/10/Superintendent-Johnson_F-1320x880.jpg 1320w" sizes="(max-width: 387px) 100vw, 387px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Chicago Police Department Superintendent Eddie Johnson (Photo: Chicago Police Department Graphic Arts Section)</p></div>
<h2>WHEN:</h2>
<p>Oct. 13<br />
7:45 a.m. to 2 p.m.</p>
<h2>WHERE:</h2>
<p>Student Center West, 2nd floor<br />
828 S. Wolcott Ave.</p>
<h2>DETAILS:</h2>
<p>8:35-9:50 a.m.<br />
<strong>Resources for Research in Minority Populations:Â Updates on the NIH&#8217;s All of Us Research Program andÂ the Center for Health Equity Research at UIC</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Dr. Martha Daviglus, associate vice chancellor for research and director of the Institute for Minority Health Research at UIC</li>
<li>Dr. Robert Winn, associate vice chancellor for community-based practice at UIC and director of the University of Illinois Cancer Center &#8211;Â <em>When CommunityÂ Meets Science: Struggles in the 21<sup>st</sup>Â Century</em></li>
<li>Maria Argos, associate professor of epidemiology and biostatistics at the UIC School of Public Health</li>
<li>Karriem Watson, director of community engagement at the University of Illinois Cancer Center</li>
<li>Joyce Hunter, senior advisor to the director of the National Institute on Minority Health and Health Disparities &#8211;Â <em>Social Determinants of Health, Precision Medicine andÂ Domestic Violence: the NIH Perspective</em></li>
</ul>
<p>10:15-11:05 a.m.<br />
<strong>Violence in Our Society: Intervention Strategies</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Heidi Stevens, columnist at the Chicago Tribune &#8211;Â <em>The #MeToo Movement: An Historical Opportunity?</em></li>
<li>Bryan Cressey, founder of Above and Beyond Family Recovery Center &#8211;Â <em>A Radically New Approach to Rehabilitation From Substance Abuse</em></li>
<li>Gabrielle Henley, chair of the Domestic Violence Ministry for Trinity Church of Christ &#8211;Â <em>Breaking the Cycle of Domestic Violence</em></li>
</ul>
<p>11:05 a.m.-12:30 p.m.<br />
<strong>Gun Violence Forum</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Daniel Kleinhubert, chief of training at the Lake County States Attorney&#8217;s Office &#8211;Â <em>Legislative Framework for Acquisition of Guns in Illinois: Pitfalls and Shortcomings</em></li>
<li>Dr. Deborah Kuhls, professor of surgery at the University of Nevada, Las Vegas, and chair of Committee of Trauma/Injury Prevention Taskforce at the American College of Surgeons &#8211;Â <em>The Las Vegas Mass Shooting: Lessons Learned</em></li>
<li>Glen Brooks Jr., director of public engagement at the Chicago Police Department &#8211;Â <em>Donâ€™t Kill a Dream, Save a Life: Violence Prevention</em></li>
<li>Eddie Johnson, superintendent of the Chicago Police Department &#8211;Â <em>Update on Gun Violence in Chicago</em></li>
</ul>
<p>This free conference is sponsored by the UIC College of Medicine departments of surgery, medicine and emergency medicine. <a href="https://www.eventbrite.com/e/bridging-the-gap-guns-prevention-health-tickets-50282743038" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Registration</a> is requested in advance.</p>
